{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569507"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22255"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22255"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.05,0.37,0.02,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107776"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15220"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22255"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90208"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40187"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107776"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless ulcer on his penis that developed one week ago. He reports no other symptoms. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is sexually active with multiple partners and does not consistently use barrier protection. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a single, non-tender, indurated ulcer with clean edges on the glans penis and non-tender inguinal lymphadenopathy. Serology for syphilis is positive. There is no evidence of neurological, ocular, or auditory involvement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral doxycycline","Intravenous benzylpenicillin","Intramuscular benzylpenicillin","Intramuscular ceftriaxone","Intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended first-line treatment for early syphilis (primary, secondary, or early latent) without central nervous system, ocular, or auditory involvement. This long-acting formulation provides sustained penicillin levels necessary to eradicate \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E with a single intramuscular dose. It is essential to use the correct formulation, as using a short-acting penicillin can result in treatment failure and ongoing transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExpert advice is recommended for people with penicillin allergy. Depending on the severity and type of allergy, the options include desensitisation, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eintramuscular ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is a short-acting penicillin and is reserved for neurosyphilis, ocular, or otic syphilis, where high and sustained serum and cerebrospinal fluid levels are required. It does not provide the prolonged low-level exposure needed to clear early syphilis and is not appropriate for uncomplicated cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is also a short-acting formulation and is not effective for early syphilis, as it does not maintain adequate tissue levels over time. Confusing benzylpenicillin with benzathine benzylpenicillin is a common and significant error that can lead to treatment failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is critical to distinguish between benzathine benzylpenicillin (long-acting, for early syphilis) and benzylpenicillin (short-acting, for neurosyphilis and other indications). Using the wrong formulation can result in inadequate treatment, persistent infection, and increased risk of complications and transmission.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Benzathine benzylpenicillin is the first-line treatment for early syphilis without central nervous system, eye, or ear involvement.","Benzathine benzylpenicillin is long-acting, whereas benzylpenicillin is short-acting and not appropriate for uncomplicated early syphilis.","Correct identification and administration of the appropriate penicillin formulation is essential to ensure effective syphilis treatment."],"references":["Ong JJ, Bourne C, Dean JA, Ryder N, Cornelisse VJ, Murray S, Kenchington P, Moten A, Gibbs C, Maunsell S, Davis T, Michaels J, Medland NA. Australian sexually transmitted infection (STI) management guidelines for use in primary care, 2022 update. Sexual Health. 2023;20(1):1-8. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/syphilis/","Therapeutic Guidelines. Syphilis [published 2021 Mar]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed 2025 Jul 2. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90208"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22255"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90208"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-02T18:18:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-02T18:19:11+09:30"},"relationships":{